<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &gt; And the new ST movie – Nemesis. I wonder if the estate of H. Beam Piper is getting a cut? (Piper wrote the novel Space Viking, in which the starship Enterprise is built, the stolen. The company that built it made a second ship to go after it, the Nemesis) I wonder if the Hollywood nitwits even know of Piper?</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
 No, they don't care. they'll use the name, even if they're aware of Piper. For the Star Fleet Battles game (not 'official' Trek), they had a major expansion boxed set called &quot;Federation and Empire&quot; I just about freaked, until I saw they meant the UFP and the Klingons...<br>
<br>
 For anyone who hasn't read Piper, the novel mentioned above(&quot;<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0824014278/qid=1021059386/sr=1-1/ref=sr_1_1/103-0049810-7008661">Space Viking</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->&quot;) is widely seen as one of the best, and a great read for space travel/battles.<br>
<br>
The story is a bit more of a turn-around for trekkers: The Enterprise is stolen, and the nut (Dunnan) who leads the theft shoots up the wedding of the girl he's been following. The theft of the ship and all it's gear puts the investors who funded it into debt, stopping the yards in the middle of starting work on the second ship. The guy (Trask) who married the now dead girl puts his entire fortune into finishing &amp; fitting out the second ship to hunt the enterprise and Dunnan.<br>
 The second ship is called Nemesis, and they are the good guys, even though they are self described &quot;professional robbers &amp; murderers&quot; (Space Vikings)<br>
<br>
 Space Viking is the novel of Piper's which is historically farthest ahead of our present, being a few thousand years after Humans discovered hyperdrive. The Terran Federation has fallen (Just after the book &quot;<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0441117597/qid=1021062577/sr=1-7/ref=sr_1_7/103-0049810-7008661">Cosmic Computer</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->&quot; which is excellent), and the Sword Worlds discoverd that the old federation is gone, with various planets here &amp; there, with various levels of sophistication. They go back to raid the more wealthy ones, and to set up bases on ones they can totally capture.<br>
<br>
Several good novels exist from the earlier times of the federation. In the <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0441484980/qid=1021060541/sr=1-6/ref=sr_1_6/103-0049810-7008661">Fuzzy</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> series, a new sentient race is discovered, and people of the Federation must adapt to this. Piper wrote a 3rd story in this (&quot;Fuzzies and Other People&quot;), but it was only discovered after he'd died. Other authors had since written about the Fuzzies, taking the story in odd but good directions.<br>
<br>
 One Federation story of interest here is called &quot;<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/0441842925/qid%3D1021062033/ref%3Dsr%5F11%5F0%5F1/103-0049810-7008661">Uller Uprising</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->&quot;. The natives on the mining planet Uller start slaughtering humans. The company &amp; few military there try to hold their ground, but it's months before a ship is due in, then more months until it gets anywhere -and more months back! They'll be long dead, unless they can come up with something.<br>
 One of thee people on Uller worked on another mine planet -On NIffleheim, they mined the flourine atmosphere by dropping nuclear charges down into it, and scooping up the uprising rare gasses! What follows is a frantic effort to use what they knew, what they could get from a romantic spy-thriller novel set in the days of the Manhattan Project, and what they can invent to save their lives and the colony.<br>
<br>
Piper's &quot;Future History&quot; is a good one for SF readers or roleplayers. Full of oddities -it was written in the early 1960s, so much of what we take form granted isn't known: Guns look &amp; work like post-world war 2, missiles are fairly dumb and unguided rockets &amp; naval guns are the usual for spaceship combat. All this, while they use total conversion power plants (E=MC^2 conversion...) in ships! Plutonium is packaged into complete power cells, from big enough to run a small ship, to tiny ones for lighters &amp; flashlights. Telerobotics is used fairly often, but scientists &amp; engineers use slide-rules!<br>
